You said:
How does Sam.gov work
ChatGPT said:

SAM.gov (System for Award Management) is the U.S. government’s official database for companies, nonprofits, and individuals who want to do business with the federal government — including getting paid for contracts, receiving grants, or qualifying for federal assistance.

Here’s how it works:

1. Purpose

  • Vendor registration – Before you can bid on federal contracts or receive federal grant money, you must be registered in SAM.gov.

  • Search tool – Anyone can use it to look up federal contract opportunities, grant listings, and information about registered entities.

  • Payment processing – Federal agencies use SAM records to ensure you can legally get paid.

2. Registration Process

  1. Create a Login.gov account – This is your secure sign-in for all federal systems.

  2. Gather information:

    • Legal business name and address (matching IRS records)

    • Taxpayer Identification Number (TIN/EIN)

    • Bank account info for electronic funds transfer

    • Unique Entity ID (UEI) – SAM generates this when you register (it replaced the old DUNS number in 2022).

  3. Complete the online registration – This includes answering questions about your business type, size, ownership, and whether you qualify for small business or socio-economic programs (e.g., veteran-owned, woman-owned).

  4. Certify and submit – You legally affirm that the info is correct.

  5. Renew annually – Your registration must be updated each year to stay active.

3. Finding Opportunities

  • Contract Opportunities – Search current solicitations, requests for quotes, and invitations for bids.

  • Grant Opportunities – Browse or filter by agency, funding type, or eligibility.

  • Entity Information – Look up other registered businesses for teaming or subcontracting.

4. How Agencies Use It

  • Contracting officers verify that a vendor is active in SAM before awarding a contract.

  • Payment offices pull banking info from SAM to make electronic payments.

  • Compliance checks are run for things like debarment or suspension.

5. Cost

  • Registration is free — any site that tries to charge you for SAM registration is a third-party service, not the official system.

6. Common Pitfalls

  • Name mismatch – Your legal name must match IRS records exactly.

  • Expired registration – If you forget to renew, you can’t be awarded new contracts.

  • Incomplete bank info – Missing or wrong routing/account numbers will delay payment.

  • Using outdated DUNS – The system now uses UEI only.

If you’d like, I can walk you through how to use SAM.gov to actually find federal contracts or grants that fit your business or project profile — that’s the part most people miss after registering. Would you like me to do that next?

  1. Generate a list of all ZIP codes that fall within 250 miles of WA-3’s center point.

Once set up, you could have:

Does SAM.gov filter for small business set asides?
ChatGPT said:

Yes — SAM.gov does let you filter specifically for small business set-aside opportunities, both in the website’s search interface and in the API.

1. On the SAM.gov Website

When you search Contract Opportunities, you can:

  • Open the "Set Aside" filter in the left-hand panel.

  • Select one or more categories, such as:

    • Total Small Business Set-Aside (FAR 19.5)

    • 8(a) Set-Aside (FAR 19.8)

    • Service-Disabled Veteran-Owned Small Business (SDVOSB)

    • Women-Owned Small Business (WOSB)

    • HUBZone Set-Aside

    • Partial Small Business

  • SAM will then return only opportunities with those set-aside designations.

2. In the API

The v2 Contract Opportunities API uses a typeOfSetAside field (and in some cases just setAside), which you can filter on in your request payload.
For example:

json
"filters": [
  {
    "field": "typeOfSetAside",
    "operation": "IN",
    "value": ["TOTAL SMALL BUSINESS", "8A"]
  }
]

Or in shorthand if you’re only looking for one type:

json
"filters": [
  {
    "field": "typeOfSetAside",
    "operation": "EQ",
    "value": "TOTAL SMALL BUSINESS"
  }
]

3. What This Means for You

If you only want opportunities reserved for small businesses, you can:

  • In the web UI — just check the “Set Aside” filter.

  • In a custom Python tool (like the one I just built for you) — we can add typeOfSetAside to the filters so it only returns small business-eligible solicitations.

how do I get a uei from sam.gov
ChatGPT said:

Getting a UEI (Unique Entity ID) from SAM.gov is pretty straightforward — but the process depends on whether your business is already registered in SAM.gov or is new.

If You’re Already Registered

  • Good news: You already have a UEI.

  • How to find it:

    1. Log into SAM.gov.

    2. Go to Workspace → My Entity Registrations.

    3. Click your entity name — your 12-character UEI will be listed at the top of the entity summary.

If You’re Not Registered Yet

  1. Go to SAM.gov.

  2. Sign in with your Login.gov account (create one if you don’t have it).

  3. From the homepage, click “Get Started” under “Register Your Entity or Get a Unique Entity ID”.

  4. Choose “Get Unique Entity ID” (without full registration) if you just need the ID for grants, reporting, etc., or “Register Entity” if you plan to bid on federal contracts.

  5. Fill in:

    • Legal Business Name (exactly as on your tax records)

    • Physical address (matching IRS or state business registry)

    • Taxpayer Identification Number (TIN/EIN) if required for your purpose.

  6. Submit and verify — SAM.gov will issue your UEI instantly in most cases.

Key Notes

  • The UEI replaced the DUNS Number in April 2022 — you no longer need to get a DUNS first.

  • The UEI is free from SAM.gov — if someone tries to charge you, they’re a third-party service.

  • If you need to update your UEI info, you do it in SAM.gov under your entity profile.

Got it — I’ll give you the latest version of sam_radius_search.py that:

  • Searches only small-business set-asides by default

  • Lets you change days, radius, keywords, NAICS, and more

  • Filters by ZIP to a true 250-mile radius around WA-3

Here’s the script:

python
#!/usr/bin/env python3
from __future__ import annotations
import os, sys, csv, json, math, argparse
from datetime import datetime, timedelta, timezone
from typing import Any, Dict, List, Optional, Tuple

import requests
from tenacity import retry, stop_after_attempt, wait_exponential, retry_if_exception_type
import pgeocode

try:
    import pandas as pd
except ImportError:
    pd = None

API_URL = "https://api.sam.gov/prod/opportunities/v2/search"
API_KEY_ENV = "SAM_API_KEY"

# WA-3 center point (Vancouver, WA)
WA3_CENTER_LAT = 45.6387
WA3_CENTER_LON = -122.6615
NEARBY_STATES = ["WA", "OR", "ID"]

# ---------- Geo helpers ----------
def miles_to_km(miles: float) -> float:
    return miles * 1.609344

def haversine_km(lat1, lon1, lat2, lon2):
    R = 6371.0088
    phi1, phi2 = math.radians(lat1), math.radians(lat2)
    dphi = math.radians(lat2 - lat1)
    dlambda = math.radians(lon2 - lon1)
    a = math.sin(dphi/2)**2 + math.cos(phi1)*math.cos(phi2)*math.sin(dlambda/2)**2
    return R * 2 * math.atan2(math.sqrt(a), math.sqrt(1-a))

# ---------- Notice helpers ----------
def extract_zip_from_notice(n):
    pops = n.get("placeOfPerformance", {}) or {}
    z = pops.get("zip") or pops.get("postalCode") or pops.get("postalcode")
    if z: return str(z)[:5]
    addr = pops.get("address") or {}
    z = addr.get("postalCode") or addr.get("zip")
    if z: return str(z)[:5]
    z = n.get("zip") or n.get("postalCode")
    return str(z)[:5] if z else None

def extract_state_from_notice(n):
    pops = n.get("placeOfPerformance", {}) or {}
    state = pops.get("state") or pops.get("stateCode") or pops.get("stateName") or (pops.get("address") or {}).get("state")
    return str(state)[:2].upper() if state else None

def extract_city_from_notice(n):
    pops = n.get("placeOfPerformance", {}) or {}
    return pops.get("city") or (pops.get("address") or {}).get("city")

def get_set_aside_raw(n):
    return str(n.get("typeOfSetAside") or n.get("setAside") or "")

# ---------- SB filter ----------
def normalize_set_aside(s):
    s = (s or "").strip().upper()
    for k in ["PROGRAM","SET-ASIDE","SET ASIDE","FOR","FAR","SUBPART"]:
        s = s.replace(k, "")
    s = " ".join(s.split())
    if "WOMEN OWNED" in s or "WOSB" in s: return "WOSB"
    if "ECONOMICALLY DISADVANTAGED" in s or "EDWOSB" in s: return "EDWOSB"
    if "SERVICE DISABLED" in s or "SDVOSB" in s: return "SDVOSB"
    if "HUBZONE" in s: return "HUBZONE"
    if "8A" in s or "8(A)" in s: return "8A"
    if "TOTAL SMALL" in s or s == "SMALL BUSINESS": return "TOTAL SMALL BUSINESS"
    if "PARTIAL SMALL" in s: return "PARTIAL SMALL BUSINESS"
    return s

def is_small_business_set_aside(n, allowed=None):
    norm = normalize_set_aside(get_set_aside_raw(n))
    allowed_set = allowed if allowed else {
        "TOTAL SMALL BUSINESS","PARTIAL SMALL BUSINESS","8A","WOSB","EDWOSB","SDVOSB","HUBZONE"
    }
    return norm in allowed_set

# ---------- API client ----------
class SAMClient:
    def __init__(self, api_key, url=API_URL):
        self.api_key = api_key
        self.url = url
        self.session = requests.Session()
        self.session.headers.update({"Content-Type": "application/json"})

    @retry(reraise=True, stop=stop_after_attempt(5), wait=wait_exponential(multiplier=1, min=1, max=40),
           retry=retry_if_exception_type((requests.RequestException,)))
    def search(self, payload):
        params = {"api_key": self.api_key}
        r = self.session.post(self.url, params=params, json=payload, timeout=60)
        if r.status_code == 429:
            raise requests.RequestException(f"Rate limited: {r.text}")
        r.raise_for_status()
        return r.json()

# ---------- Query builder ----------
def build_payload(posted_from, posted_to, states, limit, offset, keywords=None, naics=None):
    filters = []
    if states:
        filters.append({"field": "placeOfPerformance.state", "operation": "IN", "value": states})
    if naics:
        filters.append({"field": "naics", "operation": "IN", "value": naics})
    payload = {
        "limit": limit,
        "offset": offset,
        "sort": [{"field": "postedDate", "direction": "desc"}],
        "postedFrom": posted_from.strftime("%Y-%m-%dT%H:%M:%SZ"),
        "postedTo": posted_to.strftime("%Y-%m-%dT%H:%M:%SZ"),
        "active": True,
        "responseFields": [
            "title","solicitationNumber","naics","type","postedDate","responseDate",
            "organizationName","placeOfPerformance","classificationCode","description",
            "typeOfSetAside","setAside","award","baseType","archiveDate","website",
            "noticeId","baseURL"
        ],
        "filters": filters
    }
    if keywords:
        payload["q"] = " OR ".join([k.strip() for k in keywords if k.strip()])
    return payload

# ---------- Fetch + filter ----------
def fetch_all_notices(client, posted_from, posted_to, states, keywords, naics, max_records=3000, page_size=100):
    notices = []
    offset = 0
    while True:
        if len(notices) >= max_records: break
        data = client.search(build_payload(posted_from, posted_to, states, page_size, offset, keywords, naics))
        batch = data.get("notices") or []
        if not batch: break
        notices.extend(batch)
        if len(batch) < page_size: break
        offset += page_size
    return notices[:max_records]

def compute_radius_zip_filter(radius_miles, center_lat, center_lon):
    nomi = pgeocode.Nominatim('us')
    df = nomi._data.dropna(subset=["latitude", "longitude", "postal_code"]).copy()
    km_box = miles_to_km(radius_miles) + 30
    deg_lat = km_box / 111.0
    deg_lon = km_box / (111.0 * math.cos(math.radians(center_lat)))
    df_bb = df[
        (df["latitude"].between(center_lat - deg_lat, center_lat + deg_lat)) &
        (df["longitude"].between(center_lon - deg_lon, center_lon + deg_lon))
    ].copy()
    keep = set()
    for _, row in df_bb.iterrows():
        d_km = haversine_km(center_lat, center_lon, float(row["latitude"]), float(row["longitude"]))
        if d_km <= miles_to_km(radius_miles):
            keep.add(str(row["postal_code"])[:5])
    return nomi, keep

def enrich_and_filter_by_radius(notices, radius_miles, center_lat, center_lon, nomi, zipset):
    out = []
    for n in notices:
        z = extract_zip_from_notice(n)
        if z and z in zipset:
            out.append(n); continue
        state, city = extract_state_from_notice(n), extract_city_from_notice(n)
        lat = lon = None
        if z:
            rec = nomi.query_postal_code(z)
            if getattr(rec, "latitude", None) == getattr(rec, "latitude", None):
                lat, lon = float(rec.latitude), float(rec.longitude)
        if (lat is None or lon is None) and state and city:
            try:
                df = nomi._data
                cand = df[(df["state_code"] == state) & (df["place_name"].str.upper() == city.upper())]
                if not cand.empty:
                    lat, lon = float(cand.iloc[0]["latitude"]), float(cand.iloc[0]["longitude"])
            except Exception: pass
        if lat is not None and lon is not None:
            if haversine_km(center_lat, center_lon, lat, lon) <= miles_to_km(radius_miles):
                out.append(n)
    return out

# ---------- Output ----------
def flatten_notice(n):
    pops = n.get("placeOfPerformance", {}) or {}
    addr = pops.get("address") or {}
    return {
        "noticeId": n.get("noticeId") or n.get("id"),
        "title": n.get("title"),
        "solicitationNumber": n.get("solicitationNumber"),
        "type": n.get("type"),
        "naics": ",".join(n.get("naics") or []) if isinstance(n.get("naics"), list) else n.get("naics"),
        "postedDate": n.get("postedDate"),
        "responseDate": n.get("responseDate") or n.get("response_deadline"),
        "organizationName": n.get("organizationName"),
        "setAsideRaw": get_set_aside_raw(n),
        "setAsideNormalized": normalize_set_aside(get_set_aside_raw(n)),
        "classificationCode": n.get("classificationCode"),
        "website": n.get("website") or n.get("baseURL"),
        "place_city": pops.get("city") or addr.get("city"),
        "place_state": pops.get("state") or pops.get("stateCode") or addr.get("state"),
        "place_zip": pops.get("zip") or pops.get("postalCode") or addr.get("postalCode"),
        "description": (n.get("description") or "")[:2000]
    }

def write_outputs(notices, csv_path, json_path):
    with open(json_path, "w", encoding="utf-8") as f:
        json.dump(notices, f, ensure_ascii=False, indent=2)
    rows = [flatten_notice(n) for n in notices]
    if pd is not None:
        pd.DataFrame(rows).to_csv(csv_path, index=False)
    else:
        if rows:
            with open(csv_path, "w", newline="", encoding="utf-8") as f:
                writer = csv.DictWriter(f, fieldnames=list(rows[0].keys()))
                writer.writeheader()
                writer.writerows(rows)

# ---------- Main ----------
def main():
    parser = argparse.ArgumentParser(description="Fetch SAM.gov SB set-aside opportunities within WA-3 radius.")
    parser.add_argument("--days", type=int, default=14)
    parser.add_argument("--radius", type=float, default=250.0)
    parser.add_argument("--center-lat", type=float, default=WA3_CENTER_LAT)
    parser.add_argument("--center-lon", type=float, default=WA3_CENTER_LON)
    parser.add_argument("--states", type=str, default="WA,OR,ID")
    parser.add_argument("--keywords", type=str, default="")
    parser.add_argument("--naics", type=str, default="")
    parser.add_argument("--max-records", type=int, default=3000)
    parser.add_argument("--page-size", type=int, default=100)
    parser.add_argument("--csv", type=str, default="sam_opps_radius.csv")
    parser.add_argument("--json", type=str, default="sam_opps_radius.json")
    args = parser.parse_args()

    api_key = os.getenv(API_KEY_ENV)
    if not api_key:
        print(f"ERROR: Please set environment variable {API_KEY_ENV}", file=sys.stderr)
        sys.exit(2)

    now = datetime.now(timezone.utc)
    posted_from, posted_to = now - timedelta(days=args.days), now
    states = [s.strip().upper() for s in args.states.split(",") if s.strip()]
    keywords = [k.strip() for k in args.keywords.split(",") if k.strip()] if args.keywords else None
    naics = [n.strip() for n in args.naics.split(",") if n.strip()] if args.naics else None

    client = SAMClient(api_key)
    print(f"Fetching notices…")
    notices = fetch_all_notices(client, posted_from, posted_to, states, keywords, naics,
                                max_records=args.max_records, page_size=args.page_size)
    print(f"Total before filters: {len(notices)}")

    notices = [n for n in notices if is_small_business_set_aside(n)]
    print(f"After SB set-aside filter: {len(notices)}")

    nomi, zipset = compute_radius_zip_filter(args.radius, args.center_lat, args.center_lon)
    notices = enrich_and_filter_by_radius(notices, args.radius, args.center_lat, args.center_lon, nomi, zipset)
    print(f"After radius filter: {len(notices)}")

    write_outputs(notices, args.csv, args.json)
    print(f"Saved CSV to {args.csv}, JSON to {args.json}")

if __name__ == "__main__":
    main()
